\begin_layout Standard
The success of machine learning especially deep learning have prompted a
 new interest in scientific community to apply the machine learning method
 to solve challenges in physical problems modeled by partial differential
 equations involving spatiotemporal variables.
 Depending on the approaches used, there are several perks including deep
 learning/data-driven approaches to physical problems which includes : (1)
 ability to incorporate measurement data in the model predictions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pathak2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (2) Speed up computations by modelling computation expensive task and using
 machine learning approach as closure model to describe missing dynamics
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vinuesa2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These years, there are many approaches to apply machine learning to solve
 partial differential equations, a non-exhaustive approach to the methods
 includes Physics Informed Neural Network(PINN) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zubov2021,Raissi2019,Lin2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Reservoir Computing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pathak2018,Pathak2018a,Jiang2019,Wikner2020,Huhn2021,Doan2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Several studies attempted to solve Non linear Schr
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

{o}
\end_layout

\end_inset

dinger equation and another integrable equations using data-driven methods.
 Authors in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lin2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed two stage physics informed neural network for solving integrable
 wave equations, in which the first stage construct a PINN as usual, and
 the second stage augment the integrability conditions and difference with
 first stage training result as additional constraint to the PINN loss function.
 Another variant of PINN was done by enforcing the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{PT}$
\end_inset

symmetry condition to the Neural Network layers
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zhu2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The attractive feature of PINN is that the method is meshless, in other
 word, the training data from PINN is random sampled from an interval of
 space and time.
 Even though the PINN method might produce a nice generalization, the training
 process requires that the (sampled) breather should be enclosed in the
 training interval data.
 In a loose term, this mean that PINN is suitable for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

interpolation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from the data and might not perform well to extrapolate a phenomena beyond
 the training data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reservoir computing is a specialized version of recurrent neural network,
 contain an internal states called as reservoir with fixed but random parameters
 and an output layer which will be trained based on training data.
 Surprisingly despite the simplied learning compared to RNN, RC has shown
 superiority in learning tasks compared with RNN 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jaeger2004,Lukosevicius2009a,Chattopadhyay2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 especially in modelling dynamical systems.
 An extension of RC for partial differential equation was presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pathak2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for Kuramoto-Sivashinsky (KS) equation, an inclusion of knowledge based
 model was presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pathak2018a,Wikner2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Sensitivity of the spectral radius of adjacency matrix was investigated
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jiang2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and Bayesian optimization was employed to select the best hyperparameters
 for each ESN realization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Racca2021,Huhn2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This research tries to apply reservoir computing approach to the non-linear
 Schr
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

{o}
\end_layout

\end_inset

dinger equations using reservoir computing.
 NLS is an ubiquitous equation in physics that models many phenomena likes
 optics, ocean waves with modulating amplitude, rogue waves etc.
 In particular, we would like to train the phenomena of the occurence of
 rogue waves modelled by the NLS equation.
 To the best of our knowledge, only 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jiang2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which attempted to simulate NLS using Reservoir Computing, in which the
 authors simulated periodic Akhmadiev breather, Kutnezov-Ma solitons and
 second order periodic breather collision.
 The authors concluded that the second order breather collision is more
 unpredictable compared to the first order breather simulation.
 Our research is different by the fact that we use higher order breather
 as a training data (fifth order), and our training data is not only for
 one period, thus the RC has not yet encounter breather's peak.
 Furthermore, we employ parallel reservoir approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pathak2018,Wikner2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which has shown superiority in simulating the spatio-temporal problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This report is organized into four sections.
 This section present a short literature review and motivation about the
 studies.
 Section present a brief introduction about parallel reservoir computing.
 An explanation about training data, typical result of simulation and impact
 of several hyperparameters are discussed in section.
 Finally section provides a conclusion and an overview of further research
 direction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reservoir Computing
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Reservoir-Computing"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main principle in reservoir computing is the separation between internal
 states (reservoir) and the readout learning.
 As opposed to the backward propagation method which trains both the states
 and output parameters, the training in reservoir computing only applies
 to the readout.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The listening process correspond to constructing reservoir and evolve them
 based on input and previous states.
 The reservoir computing adopted was the non-leaky type given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{i} & =\tanh\left(\rho Wr_{i-1}+W_{in}u_{i-1}\right)\label{eq:Internal_State}\\
\hat{\psi}_{i} & =W_{out}\omega(r_{i})\label{eq:Readout}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is an adjecency matrix which usually set to ensure 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Echo States Property
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jaeger2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This condition express that the effect of previous state and previous input
 at future state should vanish gradually at future time.
 The adjecency matrix is set to be sparsely connected and random to ensure
 that the reservoir is rich enough for learning phase.
 The input coupling matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{in}$
\end_inset

 is a sparse matrix whose entries magnitude not more than 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the approximate number of non-zero element at each row is
 fixed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the prediction phase, the input vector 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Internal_State"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is replaced by the recent available prediction from the readout (equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Output"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) using the output matrix obtained during the training phase.
 However, as the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 consist of overlapping domain, then the output should be constructed by
 combining information from the neighbouring reservoir 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}^{(k-1)},y_{i}^{(k)}y_{i}^{(k+1)}$
\end_inset

.
 Calling this prediction as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{v}_{i}^{(k)}$
\end_inset

, then the steps in prediction phase are: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}^{(k)}=W_{out}^{k}\hat{r}_{i}^{(k)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Construct 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{v}_{i}^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 based on 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}^{(k-1)},y_{i}^{(k)}y_{i}^{(k+1)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Update the reservoir states: 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i+1}^{(k)}=\tanh\left(W^{(k)}r_{i}^{(k)}+W_{in}^{(k)}\tilde{v}_{i}^{(k)}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The implementation of the reservoir computing is based on modification of
 the code 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Martinuzzi2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which provide implementations of the reservoir computing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this research, we follows the parallel RC 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pathak2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which split the spatial data into overlapping domains and train multiple
 reservoirs for each data chunk.
 The reasoning of splitting the data is that the exchange of information
 between two very far seperated spatial grid is not immediate, thus creating
 reservoir state modelling a connection between faraway points is not physical
 and also a waste of computation effort.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega:\mathbb{R}^{M}\to\mathbb{R}^{M}$
\end_inset

 is a nonlinear feature transformation of the reservoir 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chattopadhyay2020,Pathak2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 An example of nonlinear transformation which proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pathak2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\omega_{1}(r) & =\begin{cases}
r_{j} & j\text{ is odd }\\
r_{j}^{2} & j\text{ is even }
\end{cases}\label{eq:nlat1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

For breivity we will denote the even part of transformation as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\omega}_{1}(r)=r^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Pathak2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 noted that the non-linear transformation break the odd symmetry present
 in the reservoir computing.
 Study 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chattopadhyay2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 examined different non-linear transformations for simulations of Lorenz-96
 system, which are inspired by the non-linearity present in the simulated
 equation.
 They conclude that the non-linear transformation enhance the predictive
 capability of the simulations, however they did not give conclusive result
 about which non-linearity transformation should be used, as all the transformat
ions give comparable result.
 Another experiment on the non-linearity effect was done in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pyle2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 comparing several other non-linear transformation such as 2.2 and 1.8 power,
 tanh, exp and sin on the even elements.
 The numerical experiment on Lorenz-63 showed that square-even transformation
 had the best performance.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Barbosa2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 showed that an improvement of the RC prediction can be achieved by respecting
 the symmetry of the equation present in the original system into the reservoir
 computing.
 As the NLS equation has an odd symmetry, the non-linear transformation
 that should be employed should preserve this symmetry.
 For that respect, we propose several alternatives non-linear transformation,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\omega}_{2}(r)=\left|r\right|r$
\end_inset

, the odd version of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:nlat1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\omega}_{3}(r)=r^{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\omega}_{4}(r)=\sgn(r)\sqrt{\left|x\right|}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Training Process
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The loss function is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E^{(k)}=\min_{W_{out}^{k}}\sum_{i=1}^{N_{train}}\left\Vert W_{out}^{(k)}\omega(r_{i}^{(k)})-s_{i}^{(k)}\right\Vert _{2}^{2}+\beta\left\Vert W_{out}^{(k)}\right\Vert ^{2}\label{eq:Cost_Function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In essential, the training can be done by using any method to solve linear
 least square problem.
 By defining the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 as a matrix whose 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th column is vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 respectively, then the training process is equivalent to solve the following
 matrix equation: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\mathbf{R}\mathbf{R}^{T}+\beta\mathbf{I}\right)W_{out}^{T}=\mathbf{R}\mathbf{S}^{T}
\]

\end_inset

 with notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

 denotes the conjugate transpose of matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix with suitable dimension.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several literature have discussed the importance of hyperparameters tuning
 to the prediction capability of the reservoir computing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jiang2019,Lukosevicius2012a,Racca2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Racca2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 observed that varying spectral radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and entries magnitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, does not neccessarily require reinitialization of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{in}$
\end_inset

, thus this enable optimization of these parameters at every realization
 of reservoir as done in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Huhn2021,Racca2021,Barbosa2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This study varied only the spectral radius due to computational concern
 using linear grid search between 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0.4,1.5\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we would like to investigate the generalizability of the reservoir computing
 with different dynamics compared to training data, a robust cross validation
 is an essential step.
 The cross validation was run by using the recycled validation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Racca2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which deemed as robust and efficient as the training only once need to
 done for every hyperparameter.
 The recycled parameter trained the reservoir using the whole training set,
 and then run feedback/prediction mode on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 slices of training data based on exact reservoir states at the beginning
 of each slice of cross validation set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simulation Setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We trained a set of reservoirs to learn a simulation which governed by the
 NLS equation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial\tau}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial\xi^{2}}+\left|\psi\right|^{2}\psi=0
\]

\end_inset

with the amplitude envelope 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\xi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a function of propagation distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 and co-moving time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 A well known analytic solution of NLs is given by Akhmadiev breather given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(\xi,t)=\left[1+\frac{2(1-2a)\cosh\left(\lambda t\right)+i\lambda\sinh\left(\lambda t\right)}{\sqrt{2a}\cos\left(\Omega x\right)-\cosh\left(\lambda t\right)}\right]e^{it}
\]

\end_inset

the behaviour of the solution is governed by a single parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in(0,0.5)$
\end_inset

, another parameters are related with 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, namely the fundamental wave number 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=2\sqrt{1-2a}$
\end_inset

 and growth factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\sqrt{8a(1-2a)}$
\end_inset

.
 Based on this fundamental solution, higher order maximal intensity breather
 can be constructed by choosing particular 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2},a_{3}\ldots,a_{k}$
\end_inset

 such that under particular phase and amplitude ,the breathers collides
 at particular time and position resulting at a higher peak with the procedure
 given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chin2016a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We simulated the construction of 5
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 order breather on a uniform background describing a highly non-linear situation.
 The objective of this simulation is to investigate under what conditions
 the Reservoir Computing can learn and simulate the maximum peak amplitude
 of a breather in NLS.
 For that purpose, we intentionally hide the peak of thr breather from the
 training data and preserve it as a part of test set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
