\begin_layout Standard
The training and test data is generated by using 6th order split-step method
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yoshida1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 implemented in Julia library the NonlinearSchrodinger.jl 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ashour2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A brief explanation of the split-step method is given in Appendix.
 The initial condition was prepared according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chin2016a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which generate the initial condition for maximum intensity soliton via
 Darboux Transformation.
 The modulation parameter used in generating the training set is 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=0.4802$
\end_inset

 in which there exists a unique maximum intensity soliton up to fifth order.
 The length of the spatial domain is one spatial period 
\begin_inset Formula $[-L/2,L/2]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $L=2\pi/\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 256 spatial nodes.
 The simulation was started from 
\begin_inset Formula $t=-2$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=5\cdot10^{-4}$
\end_inset

 and the peaks was achieved after , meaning there are 4000 time grids between
 the start of training data and the peak.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NLS_train_snapshot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustrate the complexity of the result that we want to achieve.
 The simulations begin with relatively uniform amplitude , toward 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, a higher order breather wave representing the rogue waves occurs.
 
\end_layout

